1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,478
Part Four introduces containers using Apptainer.

2
00:00:02,478 --> 00:00:07,021
Containers package an application and its libraries into a portable image.

3
00:00:07,021 --> 00:00:14,043
On RCC, the operational reason is especially important: a large Conda environment contains thousands of small files.

4
00:00:14,043 --> 00:00:21,890
If those files are repeatedly opened from network storage by many jobs, metadata and random input-output can dominate runtime.

5
00:00:21,890 --> 00:00:29,738
A read-only Apptainer S I F image consolidates that software stack into one managed artifact and is suitable for

6
00:00:29,738 --> 00:00:30,977
shared high-performance computing.

7
00:00:30,977 --> 00:00:38,824
We will distinguish the image from project data, explain cache and temporary storage, cover bind mounts and GPU access,

8
00:00:38,824 --> 00:00:42,955
and show how Snakemake associates a container with a rule.

9
00:00:42,955 --> 00:00:49,786
A Conda environment can contain tens of thousands of files: Python modules, shared libraries, metadata records,

10
00:00:49,786 --> 00:00:51,494
executables, and package caches.

11
00:00:51,494 --> 00:00:58,325
Starting a command may trigger many opens, stats, library searches, and imports before useful computation begins.

12
00:00:58,325 --> 00:01:01,741
On local solid-state storage this may be acceptable.

13
00:01:01,741 --> 00:01:08,572
On shared network storage, hundreds of simultaneous jobs can turn environment startup into a metadata bottleneck.

14
00:01:08,572 --> 00:01:14,549
The result may look like slow software even though the CPU is mostly waiting.

15
00:01:14,549 --> 00:01:22,662
Containers address this by packaging the software stack into a smaller number of image artifacts and by making the

16
00:01:22,662 --> 00:01:24,369
environment immutable and reproducible.

17
00:01:24,369 --> 00:01:28,662
A container image packages user-space software, libraries, and selected configuration.

18
00:01:28,662 --> 00:01:35,101
It does not include a separate hardware machine and normally shares the host Linux kernel.

19
00:01:35,101 --> 00:01:43,258
Apptainer is designed for multi-user high-performance computing and runs processes with the user identity rather than a privileged daemon

20
00:01:43,258 --> 00:01:43,687
model.

21
00:01:43,687 --> 00:01:50,126
The image is not the correct place for active project data, credentials, or patient information.

22
00:01:50,126 --> 00:01:56,995
Project inputs and outputs remain in approved storage and are made visible through explicit bind mounts.

23
00:01:56,995 --> 00:02:04,293
Containers improve reproducibility of software, but they do not validate algorithms, reference data, parameters, or scientific interpretation.

24
00:02:04,293 --> 00:02:08,387
Apptainer commonly uses the Singularity Image Format, or S I F.

25
00:02:08,387 --> 00:02:13,226
A SIF image can contain a compressed read-only filesystem plus metadata and signatures.

26
00:02:13,226 --> 00:02:19,181
Read-only images reduce accidental drift: a job cannot silently install a different library into the image.

27
00:02:19,181 --> 00:02:22,531
The same image can be used by many jobs.

28
00:02:22,531 --> 00:02:26,998
Record the image source, digest or checksum, creation recipe, and validation status.

29
00:02:26,998 --> 00:02:31,093
Do not rely only on a floating tag such as latest.

30
00:02:31,093 --> 00:02:38,165
A container is a versioned research dependency and should be managed with the same care as a reference genome

31
00:02:38,165 --> 00:02:39,282
or analysis script.

32
00:02:39,282 --> 00:02:41,888
Container workflows involve several storage locations.

33
00:02:41,888 --> 00:02:45,799
The SIF image is a durable, versioned software artifact.

34
00:02:45,799 --> 00:02:54,053
The Apptainer cache stores downloaded layers and should use an RCC-approved path; uncontrolled caches on a shared home directory

35
00:02:54,053 --> 00:02:57,095
can consume space and create metadata traffic.

36
00:02:57,095 --> 00:03:01,874
Temporary build or extraction space should use local scratch when possible.

37
00:03:01,874 --> 00:03:07,522
Project data remains in approved shared storage and is bound into the container.

38
00:03:07,522 --> 00:03:14,473
Distinguishing these locations prevents accidental data loss and avoids turning network storage into a scratch disk.

39
00:03:14,473 --> 00:03:21,425
The RCC should publish standard environment variables and paths for image stores, caches, and temporary directories.

40
00:03:21,425 --> 00:03:26,885
Only run images from trusted sources or images built from reviewed definitions.

41
00:03:26,885 --> 00:03:29,616
Prefer immutable digests over floating tags.

42
00:03:29,616 --> 00:03:35,532
Calculate and record a checksum for a SIF image when it is transferred.

43
00:03:35,532 --> 00:03:37,807
Inspect image metadata and labels.

44
00:03:37,807 --> 00:03:43,268
Record the base image, installed package versions, build date, and definition file.

45
00:03:43,268 --> 00:03:46,909
Scan or review images according to institutional policy.

46
00:03:46,909 --> 00:03:51,914
Most importantly, validate the scientific behavior with synthetic and reference data.

47
00:03:51,914 --> 00:03:59,196
A correctly signed image can still contain an unsuitable algorithm, outdated database, or incorrect default parameter.

48
00:03:59,196 --> 00:04:03,746
Trust has both a software-supply-chain component and a scientific-validation component.

49
00:04:03,746 --> 00:04:07,098
Apptainer exec runs a command inside an image.

50
00:04:07,098 --> 00:04:11,706
Start with a harmless version check, then a small synthetic test.

51
00:04:11,706 --> 00:04:17,571
The clean environment option reduces accidental inheritance of host variables that could change behavior.

52
00:04:17,571 --> 00:04:22,598
The contain-all or site-recommended isolation options may be appropriate depending on policy.

53
00:04:22,598 --> 00:04:25,949
Record the full command in the workflow log.

54
00:04:25,949 --> 00:04:32,652
Avoid interactive changes inside writable sandboxes for production work because those changes are difficult to reproduce.

55
00:04:32,652 --> 00:04:40,611
If a command depends on locale, threads, temporary paths, or license variables, declare them explicitly and document why they

56
00:04:40,611 --> 00:04:41,449
are needed.

57
00:04:41,449 --> 00:04:47,793
A bind mount makes a host path visible at a chosen path inside the container.

58
00:04:47,793 --> 00:04:50,331
Bind source data read-only whenever possible.

59
00:04:50,331 --> 00:04:52,869
Bind a dedicated result directory read-write.

60
00:04:52,869 --> 00:04:55,407
Bind node-local scratch for temporary work.

61
00:04:55,407 --> 00:05:03,443
Avoid binding your entire home directory merely for convenience, because that makes hidden configuration and credentials visible and reduces

62
00:05:03,443 --> 00:05:03,866
reproducibility.

63
00:05:03,866 --> 00:05:11,902
Use stable internal paths such as slash data, slash results, and slash tmp so the command is independent of

64
00:05:11,902 --> 00:05:13,593
the host project layout.

65
00:05:13,593 --> 00:05:17,400
Verify ownership and permissions before starting thousands of jobs.

66
00:05:17,400 --> 00:05:21,219
A container does not make random network input-output fast.

67
00:05:21,219 --> 00:05:29,282
The executable may be packaged efficiently, but inputs, outputs, caches, and temporary files still follow the underlying storage behavior.

68
00:05:29,282 --> 00:05:31,828
Keep compressed inputs compressed when supported.

69
00:05:31,828 --> 00:05:37,344
Stage files that require random access or many temporary writes to node-local scratch.

70
00:05:37,344 --> 00:05:42,012
Avoid writing package caches or application caches into the project directory.

71
00:05:42,012 --> 00:05:46,256
Limit the number of tiny output files and organize directories.

72
00:05:46,256 --> 00:05:53,470
A container can even make performance worse if every job independently pulls an image from a registry.

73
00:05:53,470 --> 00:05:59,835
Pre-stage approved images and use a shared read-only image location or an RCC-supported cache strategy.

74
00:05:59,835 --> 00:06:07,556
For a GPU job, request the GPU through Slurm and run Apptainer with the N V option so the

75
00:06:07,556 --> 00:06:12,433
relevant NVIDIA devices and host driver libraries are available inside the container.

76
00:06:12,433 --> 00:06:20,154
The image should contain compatible user-space frameworks such as CUDA-enabled PyTorch or TensorFlow, but it should not attempt to

77
00:06:20,154 --> 00:06:22,186
replace the host kernel driver.

78
00:06:22,186 --> 00:06:29,094
Test compatibility on a small allocation and use nvidia-smi both on the host allocation and, where appropriate,

79
00:06:29,094 --> 00:06:30,313
inside the container.

80
00:06:30,313 --> 00:06:34,377
Record image digest, GPU type, driver, framework version, and command.

81
00:06:34,377 --> 00:06:40,066
GPU access does not change the need to optimize data loading and batch size.

82
00:06:40,066 --> 00:06:46,912
Snakemake can associate a container image with a rule and execute the workflow using the Apptainer deployment method.

83
00:06:46,912 --> 00:06:52,997
This places the software dependency next to the declared inputs, outputs, threads, resources, log, and command.

84
00:06:52,997 --> 00:06:58,701
Use an RCC-supported Apptainer prefix or image store so jobs do not repeatedly download images.

85
00:06:58,701 --> 00:07:05,166
The rule should still use tmpdir or a shadow pattern when the tool needs local temporary work.

86
00:07:05,166 --> 00:07:10,490
Pin the image to an immutable digest or version and record it in reports.

87
00:07:10,490 --> 00:07:15,434
Test both the workflow logic and the image before scaling to production data.

88
00:07:15,434 --> 00:07:22,706
A production image should be built from a version-controlled Apptainer definition file or an equivalent reviewed recipe.

89
00:07:22,706 --> 00:07:29,122
Build in an approved environment, because image construction may require privileges or a remote builder.

90
00:07:29,122 --> 00:07:31,688
Record base images and package versions.

91
00:07:31,688 --> 00:07:36,821
Run automated smoke tests, workflow tests with synthetic data, and scientific validation.

92
00:07:36,821 --> 00:07:44,093
Publish the image to an approved registry or image store, record the digest, and make it read-only.

93
00:07:44,093 --> 00:07:48,370
Rebuild through the recipe rather than modifying an existing image.

94
00:07:48,370 --> 00:07:54,786
Deprecate images that contain security problems or obsolete references, but preserve provenance for completed analyses.

95
00:07:54,786 --> 00:07:57,134
The container rules are these.

96
00:07:57,134 --> 00:07:59,481
Use trusted, immutable SIF images.

97
00:07:59,481 --> 00:08:02,768
Record source, digest, build recipe, and validation.

98
00:08:02,768 --> 00:08:05,585
Keep project data outside the image.

99
00:08:05,585 --> 00:08:11,219
Bind source data read-only, results deliberately, and temporary space to local scratch.

100
00:08:11,219 --> 00:08:14,506
Place caches and images in RCC-approved locations.

101
00:08:14,506 --> 00:08:17,323
Use clean environments and explicit commands.

102
00:08:17,323 --> 00:08:23,896
Request GPUs through Slurm and use the Apptainer GPU option only for compatible images.

103
00:08:23,896 --> 00:08:30,000
In Snakemake, pin the container per rule or workflow and avoid repeated pulls.

104
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:37,512
Remember that containers improve software reproducibility and startup I/O, but good data input-output patterns, performance measurement,

105
00:08:37,512 --> 00:08:39,860
and scientific validation remain essential.

